    subgraph U1["Unit 1: Foundations of American Democracy"]
        U1S1["I know what natural rights are — life, liberty, and property according to John Locke"]
        U1S2["I know what social contract theory is — a voluntary agreement between people and government"]
        U1S3["I know what popular sovereignty is — government getting its power from the people's consent"]
        U1S4["I know that Locke and Montesquieu were key Enlightenment thinkers who influenced American democracy"]
        U1S5["I understand how the Declaration of Independence reflects natural rights and social contract theory"]
        U1S6["I know that the Declaration of Independence asserts the right to alter or abolish unjust government"]
        U1S7["I know what a republican form of government means — government run by elected representatives"]
        U1S8["I understand how the Constitution establishes a representative republic rather than a direct democracy"]
        U1S9["I know what participatory democracy means — where everyday citizens are actively involved in politics"]
        U1S12["I can explain the differences between participatory, pluralist, and elite democracy models"]
        U1S10["I know what pluralist democracy means — where competing interest groups shape government policy"]
        U1S11["I know what elite democracy means — government controlled by a small group of wealthy, powerful people"]
        U1S13["I understand how each model of democracy is reflected in different American political institutions"]
        U1S14["I know what limited government is — constitutional restrictions on government power to protect individual rights"]
        U1S15["I understand the tension between government power and individual liberty as a core tension in American democracy"]
        U1S16["I know weaknesses of the Articles of Confederation, including no national taxing power"]
        U1S19["I understand why the Articles of Confederation were too weak to run the country"]
        U1S17["I know that the Articles had no national executive or national judiciary"]
        U1S18["I know that the Articles required unanimous consent for amendments and supermajority for legislation"]
        U1S20["I know that the Articles gave Congress no power to regulate interstate commerce"]
        U1S21["I understand how Shays Rebellion showed the country needed a stronger national government"]
        U1S22["I know that the Constitutional Convention of 1787 was called because of the failures of the Articles"]
        U1S23["I know that the Virginia Plan was favoring large states with representation based on population"]
        U1S24["I know that the New Jersey Plan was favoring small states with equal representation"]
        U1S25["I know that the Great Compromise created a two-chamber Congress — the House (based on population) and the Senate (equal representation per state)"]
        U1S26["I know that the Three-Fifths Compromise counting enslaved people was 3/5 of a person for representation purposes"]
        U1S27["I understand the Electoral College as a compromise for selecting the president balancing popular and state influence"]
        U1S28["I know what Federalists were — people who supported the Constitution and wanted a strong national government"]
        U1S29["I know what Anti-Federalists were — people who opposed the Constitution, wanted more state power, and demanded a Bill of Rights"]
        U1S30["I can explain the differences between Federalist and Anti-Federalist arguments about whether to adopt the Constitution"]
        U1S31["I know that Anti-Federalist demands led to the addition of the Bill of Rights"]
        U1S32["I understand Federalist No. 10 argument that political factions (groups with competing interests) will always exist in a free society"]
        U1S33["I understand Madisons argument in Federalist No. 10 that a big country with many competing groups actually helps prevent any one group from taking over"]
        U1S34["I understand how Federalist No. 10 argues that a representative government channels the public's views through elected representatives"]
        U1S35["I understand how Federalist No. 10 supports pluralist democracy by letting many different groups compete for influence"]
        U1S36["I understand Brutus No. 1 argument that a large republic would threaten freedom and people's ability to govern themselves"]
        U1S37["I understand Brutus No. 1 concern that the Necessary and Proper Clause (the 'elastic clause') could let the federal government expand its power with no real limit"]
        U1S38["I understand Brutus No. 1 argument that representatives in a large republic can't really know or represent the people they serve"]
        U1S39["I can explain the differences between arguments in Federalist No. 10 and Brutus No. 1 about the size of the republic"]
        U1S40["I understand Federalist No. 51 argument for separation of powers among three independent branches"]
        U1S41["I understand Madisons argument in Federalist No. 51 that you have to use people's ambition against each other to prevent power grabs"]
        U1S42["I understand how checks and balances keep any one branch from getting too powerful according to Federalist No. 51"]
        U1S43["I understand the double security concept in Federalist No. 51 — splitting power between federal and state governments gives people double protection"]
        U1S44["I know that the three branches of government is legislative, executive, and judicial"]
        U1S45["I understand separation of powers — giving each branch its own specific job"]
        U1S46["I know specific checks and balances, including veto, override, judicial review, and Senate confirmation"]
        U1S47["I understand how checks and balances maintain the balance of power among the three branches"]
        U1S48["I understand the Article V amendment process — you need 2/3 of Congress to propose and 3/4 of states to approve"]
        U1S49["I understand the formal amendment process — Congress (or a convention) proposes, then states ratify"]
        U1S50["I know that the difficulty of amending the Constitution shows the Founders wanted the Constitution to be hard to change"]
        U1S51["I know what listed (enumerated) powers are — powers specifically granted to Congress in Article I Section 8"]
        U1S52["I know examples of listed (enumerated) powers, including taxing, coining money, declaring war, and regulating commerce"]
        U1S53["I know what implied powers are — powers not specifically listed but implied by the Necessary and Proper Clause (the 'elastic clause'), AKA the Elastic Clause the Necessary and Proper Clause (the 'elastic clause') or Elastic Clause"]
        U1S54["I understand how the Necessary and Proper Clause (the 'elastic clause') enables Congress to make laws to carry out its listed (enumerated) powers"]
        U1S55["I know what reserved powers are — those retained by the states under the Tenth Amendment"]
        U1S56["I know examples of reserved powers, including education policy, marriage laws, and intrastate commerce"]
        U1S57["I know what shared (concurrent) powers are — powers shared by both federal and state governments"]
        U1S58["I know examples of shared (concurrent) powers, including taxing, borrowing money, and establishing courts"]
        U1S59["I understand the Supremacy Clause establishing federal law as supreme over conflicting state law"]
        U1S60["I understand the Commerce Clause granting Congress power to regulate interstate commerce"]
        U1S61["I understand how federalism divides and shares power between national and state governments"]
        U1S62["I know what dual federalism means — a clear division between federal and state powers"]
        U1S63["I know what cooperative federalism means — overlapping federal and state responsibilities"]
        U1S64["I can explain the differences between dual federalism and cooperative federalism as different models of the federal relationship"]
        U1S65["I understand the Fourteenth Amendment as extending due process (fair legal procedures) and equal protection to state government actions"]
        U1S66["I understand the Full Faith and Credit Clause requiring states to honor other states public acts and records"]
        U1S67["I understand McCulloch v. Maryland ruling that Congress has implied powers (powers not written out but suggested by the Constitution) under the Necessary and Proper Clause (the 'elastic clause')"]
        U1S68["I understand McCulloch v. Maryland ruling that states cannot tax federal institutions under the Supremacy Clause"]
        U1S69["I understand how McCulloch v. Maryland expanded federal power and supported a broad interpretation of the Constitution"]
        U1S70["I understand United States v. Lopez ruling that the Gun-Free School Zones Act exceeded Congress Commerce Clause power"]
        U1S71["I understand how United States v. Lopez limited federal power by narrowing the scope of the Commerce Clause"]
        U1S72["I can explain the differences between McCulloch v. Maryland and United States v. Lopez as expanding vs limiting federal power"]
        U1S73["I know what categorical grants (federal money with strict rules on how to spend it) means — federal funds given to states for specific narrowly defined purposes"]
        U1S74["I know what block grants (federal money states can spend more flexibly) means — federal funds given to states for broad policy areas with state discretion"]
        U1S75["I know what mandates are — federal requirements imposed on state and local governments"]
        U1S76["I can explain the differences between categorical grants (federal money with strict rules on how to spend it) and block grants (federal money states can spend more flexibly) in terms of federal control vs state flexibility"]
        U1S77["I know what unfunded mandates (federal requirements states must follow but don't get money for) is — federal requirements on states that do not include funding"]
        U1S78["I understand how grants and mandates shape the balance of power in the federal system"]
        U1S79["I know what devolution means — the transfer of responsibilities from the federal government to state and local governments"]
        U1S80["I understand how revenue sharing provides federal funds to states with few restrictions"]
