    subgraph U2["Unit 2: Interactions Among Branches of Government"]
        U2S1["I know that the House is having 435 members divided up based on state population with two-year terms"]
        U2S3["I can explain the differences between the structure, powers, and characteristics of the House and Senate"]
        U2S2["I know that the Senate is having 100 members with two per state serving six-year terms"]
        U2S4["I know that the House starts tax/spending bills and the Senate approves treaties and confirms presidential appointments"]
        U2S5["I know that the House has the sole power to impeach (formally charge) and the Senate has the sole power to hold the impeachment trial"]
        U2S6["I know that the Speaker of the House is the presiding officer and most powerful member of the House"]
        U2S7["I know that the Vice President is President of the Senate who casts tie-breaking votes"]
        U2S8["I know that Senate Majority Leader is the most powerful member in setting the Senate agenda"]
        U2S9["I know that Senators represent entire states while House members represent specific congressional districts"]
        U2S10["I understand the legislative process from bill introduction through committee, floor debate, and presidential action"]
        U2S11["I understand the role of committees in shaping legislation through hearings, markups, and reporting bills"]
        U2S12["I know types of congressional committees, including standing, select, joint, and conference committees"]
        U2S13["I understand the role of conference committees in reconciling House and Senate versions of bills"]
        U2S14["I understand the House Rules Committee as controlling the terms of debate and amendments for bills on the House floor"]
        U2S15["I know that Senate debate is generally unlimited unlike the more structured House"]
        U2S16["I know what a filibuster means — a Senate tactic of extended debate used to delay or prevent a vote on legislation"]
        U2S17["I know that cloture requires 60 Senate votes to end a filibuster"]
        U2S18["I understand how the filibuster gives the Senate minority party power to block legislation"]
        U2S19["I know that both chambers must pass identical versions of a bill before it is sent to the president"]
        U2S20["I understand the presidents options upon receiving a bill: sign, veto, pocket veto, or let it become law"]
        U2S21["I understand Congress power of the purse including taxing, spending, and approving the federal budget"]
        U2S22["I understand the Senates role in confirming presidential appointments including judicial nominees"]
        U2S23["I know what logrolling (trading votes — 'I'll vote for yours if you vote for mine') means — the trading of votes among legislators to pass bills of mutual interest"]
        U2S24["I know what pork barrel legislation means — spending directed at a specific district to benefit constituents"]
        U2S25["I understand how partisan politics and increasing polarization affect congressional behavior and gridlock"]
        U2S26["I understand the delegate model where representatives vote according to constituent preferences"]
        U2S27["I understand the trustee model where representatives use their own judgment when voting"]
        U2S28["I understand the politico model as a combination of delegate and trustee approaches depending on the issue"]
        U2S29["I can explain the differences between delegate, trustee, and politico models of representation"]
        U2S30["I understand how divided government can lead to legislative gridlock"]
        U2S31["I understand how party leadership including whips and caucuses influences congressional voting behavior"]
        U2S32["I understand Baker v. Carr ruling that legislative redistricting is a something the courts can decide (under the Equal Protection Clause)"]
        U2S33["I understand the one person one vote principle requiring roughly equal population in legislative districts"]
        U2S34["I know the formal constitutional powers of the president in Article II"]
        U2S35["I understand the presidents role as commander in chief of the armed forces"]
        U2S36["I understand the presidents veto power and the requirement of a two-thirds vote in both chambers to override"]
        U2S37["I understand the presidents power to negotiate treaties requiring two-thirds Senate approval"]
        U2S38["I understand the presidents appointment power for federal judges, cabinet members, and ambassadors"]
        U2S39["I understand the presidents power to grant pardons and reprieves for federal offenses"]
        U2S40["I understand the presidents power to receive ambassadors and conduct foreign policy"]
        U2S41["I understand the presidents duty to give Congress information on the State of the Union"]
        U2S42["I know informal presidential powers, including executive orders, executive agreements, and signing statements"]
        U2S43["I understand how executive orders direct federal agencies and have the force of law without congressional approval"]
        U2S44["I know what executive agreements is — international agreements made without Senate treaty ratification"]
        U2S45["I know what signing statements is — presidential interpretations of legislation that may influence implementation"]
        U2S46["I understand Federalist No. 70 argument that a single executive provides energy in the executive branch"]
        U2S47["I understand Hamiltons argument that a unitary executive ensures decisiveness, secrecy, and dispatch in governance"]
        U2S48["I understand Hamiltons argument that a single executive allows clear accountability to the public"]
        U2S49["I understand how Congress checks the president through the power to override vetoes"]
        U2S50["I understand how Congress checks the president through the power of the purse"]
        U2S51["I understand how the Senate checks the president through the treaty ratification power"]
        U2S52["I understand how the Senate checks the president through the confirmation of appointments"]
        U2S53["I understand how Congress checks the president through the impeachment and removal process"]
        U2S54["I understand how the War Powers Resolution of 1973 requires presidential notification and limits troop deployment"]
        U2S55["I understand the ongoing tension between presidential war powers and congressional authority to declare war"]
        U2S56["I understand how presidential power has expanded beyond original constitutional provisions over time"]
        U2S57["I understand how executive orders have expanded presidential domestic policy influence"]
        U2S58["I understand how presidential power expands during national crises and emergencies"]
        U2S59["I understand how executive agreements have increased presidential power in foreign affairs"]
        U2S60["I understand the growth of the Executive Office of the President as reflecting expanding presidential responsibilities"]
        U2S61["I understand the bully pulpit as the presidents ability to use media access to shape public opinion and policy"]
        U2S62["I understand how the State of the Union address allows the president to set the legislative agenda"]
        U2S63["I understand how presidential communication strategies including press conferences and social media influence policy"]
        U2S64["I understand how presidents use the mandate of the people to pressure Congress to pass their agenda"]
        U2S65["I know the structure of federal courts, including district courts, courts of appeals, and the Supreme Court"]
        U2S66["I understand the difference between original jurisdiction and appellate jurisdiction"]
        U2S67["I know that the Supreme Court has both limited original jurisdiction and broad appellate jurisdiction"]
        U2S68["I know that federal judges serve lifetime appointments during good behavior under Article III"]
        U2S69["I understand how lifetime tenure promotes judicial independence from political pressure"]
        U2S70["I know what Marbury v. Madison is — establishing the principle of judicial review"]
        U2S71["I know what judicial review is — the power of courts to strike down laws or executive actions as unconstitutional"]
        U2S72["I understand how judicial review serves as a check on the legislative and executive branches"]
        U2S73["I understand Federalist No. 78 argument that the judiciary is the least dangerous branch lacking force and will"]
        U2S74["I understand Hamiltons argument in Federalist No. 78 for judicial independence through lifetime tenure"]
        U2S75["I know what Hamiltons argument in Federalist No. 78 for judicial review is — essential to a limited constitution"]
        U2S76["I can explain the differences between Federalist No. 78 arguments about judicial power with debates over judicial activism"]
        U2S77["I know what judicial activism means — courts broadly interpreting the Constitution to shape social policy"]
        U2S78["I know what judicial restraint means — courts deferring to the elected branches and adhering to precedent"]
        U2S79["I can explain the differences between judicial activism (judges making bold decisions) and judicial restraint (judges deferring to elected branches) as competing judicial philosophies"]
        U2S80["I understand stare decisis — the principle that courts follow established precedent in deciding cases"]
        U2S81["I understand how the Supreme Court can overturn its own precedent in extraordinary circumstances"]
        U2S82["I understand the process of selecting Supreme Court cases through writs of certiorari"]
        U2S83["I understand the rule of four as requiring four justices to agree to hear a case"]
        U2S84["I understand the role of oral arguments in Supreme Court proceedings"]
        U2S85["I understand the role of amicus curiae briefs (friend-of-the-court arguments from outside groups) as friend of the court briefs filed by interested parties"]
        U2S86["I understand the difference between majority opinions, concurring opinions, and dissenting opinions"]
        U2S87["I know that majority opinions establish binding precedent as the law of the land"]
        U2S88["I understand how the Solicitor General (the government's top lawyer at the Supreme Court) represents the federal government before the Supreme Court"]
        U2S89["I understand how Congress can check the judiciary through proposing constitutional amendments"]
        U2S90["I understand how Congress can check the judiciary by changing the size or jurisdiction of federal courts"]
        U2S91["I understand how the Senate confirmation process serves as a check on judicial appointments"]
        U2S92["I understand how the president checks the judiciary through the power to appoint federal judges"]
        U2S93["I know that implementation of court decisions depends on cooperation from the executive and legislative branches"]
        U2S94["I understand the debate about whether judges should interpret the Constitution based on original meaning or as a living document"]
        U2S95["I know that the federal bureaucracy is including cabinet departments, independent agencies, and regulatory commissions"]
        U2S96["I understand the structure of the federal bureaucracy including the fifteen cabinet departments"]
        U2S97["I understand the Executive Office of the President as containing key advisory bodies like the NSC and OMB"]
        U2S98["I know what independent regulatory commissions is — agencies with quasi-legislative and quasi-judicial powers"]
        U2S99["I understand how the bureaucracy implements federal policy through rulemaking and enforcement"]
        U2S100["I understand the merit system of civil service based on qualifications rather than political patronage"]
        U2S101["I understand how the Pendleton Civil Service Act replaced the spoils system with merit-based hiring"]
        U2S102["I know what bureaucratic discretion is — the power of agencies to interpret and apply legislation"]
        U2S103["I understand how bureaucratic agencies issue regulations through the rulemaking process that have the force of law"]
        U2S104["I understand how iron triangles (tight relationships between agencies, interest groups, and congressional committees) connect bureaucratic agencies, congressional committees, and interest groups"]
        U2S105["I understand how issue networks (looser, broader groups of people who all care about the same policy area) are broader and more fluid policy communities than iron triangles (tight relationships between agencies, interest groups, and congressional committees)"]
        U2S106["I can explain the differences between iron triangles (tight relationships between agencies, interest groups, and congressional committees) and issue networks (looser, broader groups of people who all care about the same policy area) as models of policymaking relationships"]
        U2S107["I understand congressional oversight of the bureaucracy through hearings, investigations, and appropriations"]
        U2S108["I understand how Congress uses the power of the purse to control bureaucratic agency funding"]
        U2S109["I understand how the president holds the bureaucracy accountable through appointments and executive orders"]
        U2S110["I understand how the judiciary checks the bureaucracy through judicial review of agency actions and regulations"]
        U2S111["I understand how whistleblower protections encourage reporting of bureaucratic waste and abuse"]
        U2S112["I understand how the Freedom of Information Act promotes government transparency and accountability"]
