    subgraph U4["Unit 4: American Political Ideologies and Beliefs"]
        U4S1["I know what political ideology is — a consistent set of beliefs about what government should and shouldn't do"]
        U4S2["I know that the liberal-conservative spectrum (left to right) is the primary ideological framework in American politics"]
        U4S3["I know that liberals generally favor government intervention in the economy and protection of individual civil liberties"]
        U4S4["I know that conservatives generally favor limited government in the economy and traditional social values"]
        U4S5["I can explain the differences between liberal and conservative positions on the role and size of government"]
        U4S6["I know what libertarianism means — favoring minimal government intervention in both economic and social issues"]
        U4S7["I know what populism means — supporting the interests of ordinary people often favoring government economic intervention and traditional values"]
        U4S8["I can place political ideologies on a spectrum from liberal to moderate to conservative to libertarian"]
        U4S9["I understand how core American values including individualism, equality of opportunity, free enterprise, and rule of law shape political attitudes"]
        U4S10["I understand how Americans can share core values but disagree on how government should implement them"]
        U4S11["I know what political socialization (how people develop their political views) means — the process through which individuals develop their political beliefs and values"]
        U4S12["I know that family is the primary and most influential agent of political socialization (how people develop their political views)"]
        U4S13["I know that schools and education is agents of political socialization (how people develop their political views) that promote civic values"]
        U4S14["I know that peers, media, religious institutions, and social groups is agents of political socialization (how people develop their political views)"]
        U4S15["I understand how demographic factors including race and ethnicity influence political attitudes and party identification"]
        U4S16["I understand how gender influences political attitudes with women more likely to support the Democratic Party"]
        U4S17["I understand how religious beliefs and religious denomination influence political ideology and party affiliation"]
        U4S18["I understand how education level and income influence political attitudes and participation"]
        U4S19["I understand how political socialization (how people develop their political views) produces generational differences in political attitudes and behavior"]
        U4S20["I understand how political ideologies shift over time in response to events, demographics, and cultural change"]
        U4S21["I understand the concept of realignment as a dramatic long-term shift in party coalitions and dominant ideology"]
        U4S22["I understand how globalization and technological change have influenced American political ideologies"]
        U4S23["I understand how major events like the Great Depression shifted public attitudes toward greater government involvement"]
        U4S24["I understand how events like the Vietnam War and Watergate decreased public trust in government"]
        U4S25["I understand how the September 11 attacks shifted attitudes about national security and civil liberties"]
        U4S26["I understand the long-term trend of declining trust in government institutions since the 1960s"]
        U4S27["I understand the relationship between political events and shifts in ideological identification among the public"]
        U4S28["I know what public opinion means — the aggregate of attitudes and beliefs held by the adult population about political issues"]
        U4S29["I understand how scientific polling uses random sampling to accurately measure public opinion"]
        U4S30["I understand the importance of random sampling to ensure a poll is representative of the broader population"]
        U4S31["I know what sampling error (margin of error) is — the range within which the true population value likely falls"]
        U4S32["I know factors affecting poll reliability, including sample size, question wording, question order, and timing"]
        U4S33["I can make sense of a polls margin of error to determine whether differences between groups or candidates are statistically meaningful"]
        U4S34["I know potential sources of bias in polling, including leading questions, selection bias, and response bias"]
        U4S35["I can evaluate the credibility and methodological validity of public opinion polls and survey data"]
        U4S36["I understand public opinion data presented in charts, tables, graphs, and infographics"]
        U4S37["I can draw valid conclusions from polling data about trends in public opinion across demographic groups"]
        U4S38["I know that the Democratic Party platform generally aligns with liberal ideology on economic and social issues"]
        U4S39["I know that the Republican Party platform generally aligns with conservative ideology on economic and social issues"]
        U4S40["I can explain the differences between the policy platforms of the Democratic and Republican parties on specific issues"]
        U4S41["I understand how party platforms reflect ideological positions and serve as governing blueprints"]
        U4S42["I understand how competing ideologies lead to different policy proposals on the same policy issue"]
        U4S43["I understand how ideology influences government decisions on taxes, spending, regulation, and social programs"]
        U4S44["I understand liberal support for progressive taxation where higher earners pay higher tax rates"]
        U4S45["I understand liberal support for government regulation of the economy to protect consumers and workers"]
        U4S46["I understand conservative support for lower taxes and reduced government regulation to promote economic growth"]
        U4S47["I understand conservative support for free market solutions and limited government intervention in the economy"]
        U4S48["I know what supply-side economics is — the belief that tax cuts for businesses and individuals stimulate growth"]
        U4S49["I know what Keynesian economics is — the belief that government spending can stimulate the economy during downturns"]
        U4S50["I can explain the differences between supply-side and Keynesian approaches to fiscal and economic policy"]
        U4S51["I understand how ideological differences shape debates over the federal budget, national debt, and entitlement programs"]
        U4S52["I understand the debate between expanding and reducing the social safety net including Social Security, Medicare, and Medicaid"]
        U4S53["I understand liberal positions on social issues including support for expanding healthcare access and environmental regulation"]
        U4S54["I understand conservative positions on social issues including emphasis on traditional values and personal responsibility"]
        U4S55["I can explain the differences between liberal and conservative policy positions on healthcare, immigration, and environmental policy"]
        U4S56["I understand how ideological differences shape major policy debates in contemporary American politics"]
