    subgraph U5["Unit 5: Political Participation"]
        U5S1["I understand the historical expansion of suffrage through constitutional amendments"]
        U5S2["I understand the Fifteenth Amendment as prohibiting denial of voting rights based on race"]
        U5S3["I understand the Nineteenth Amendment as establishing womens right to vote"]
        U5S4["I understand the Twenty-Fourth Amendment as abolishing poll taxes in federal elections"]
        U5S5["I understand the Twenty-Sixth Amendment as lowering the voting age to eighteen"]
        U5S6["I understand the Voting Rights Act of 1965 as eliminating barriers such as literacy tests for minority voters"]
        U5S7["I know what rational-choice voting (picking whoever benefits you most) means — selecting the candidate whose policies maximize ones self-interest"]
        U5S10["I can explain the differences between rational-choice, retrospective, prospective, and party-line voting (voting for one party straight down the ballot) models"]
        U5S8["I know what retrospective voting (voting based on how things have been going) means — basing vote choice on past performance of the incumbent or party"]
        U5S9["I know what prospective voting (voting based on what you think a candidate will do) means — basing vote choice on predictions about a candidates future policy performance"]
        U5S11["I know what party-line voting (voting for one party straight down the ballot) means — voting for candidates of one political party for all offices on the ballot"]
        U5S12["I know factors that increase voter turnout, including higher education, higher income, and older age"]
        U5S13["I understand demographic patterns in voter turnout across different groups"]
        U5S14["I know what political efficacy (believing your vote and participation actually matter) means — the belief that ones participation in politics can make a difference"]
        U5S15["I understand how high political efficacy (believing your vote and participation actually matter) increases voter turnout and political engagement"]
        U5S16["I know that voter turnout is consistently higher in presidential elections than in midterm elections"]
        U5S17["I know structural barriers to voting, including registration requirements, voter ID laws, and felony disenfranchisement"]
        U5S18["I understand how institutional factors like registration deadlines and polling access affect voter turnout"]
        U5S19["I understand how reforms such as the Motor Voter Act, early voting, and mail-in voting aim to increase turnout"]
        U5S20["I understand the implications of low voter turnout for democratic representation and legitimacy"]
        U5S21["I understand the voter turnout gap between racial and ethnic groups and efforts to address it"]
        U5S22["I know what political parties are — organizations that recruit candidates, mobilize voters, and seek to win elections"]
        U5S23["I understand the key functions of parties including nominating candidates, running campaigns, and organizing government"]
        U5S24["I understand how the two-party system has dominated American politics since the early republic"]
        U5S25["I understand how winner-take-all single-member district plurality elections reinforce the two-party system"]
        U5S26["I know the three components of a political party: party in the electorate, party organization, and party in government"]
        U5S27["I know what party identification means — a voters long-term psychological attachment to a political party"]
        U5S28["I know that party identification is the strongest single predictor of how a person will vote"]
        U5S29["I know what critical elections and party realignments is — major long-term shifts in party coalitions"]
        U5S30["I understand the New Deal realignment as shifting African Americans, urban workers, and the South into different coalitions"]
        U5S31["I know what dealignment is — a weakening of party ties and an increase in the number of independent voters"]
        U5S32["I understand how candidate-centered campaigns have weakened traditional party organizational influence"]
        U5S33["I know barriers to third-party success, including winner-take-all elections, ballot access laws, and debate exclusion"]
        U5S34["I know that third parties often bring new issues to public attention that major parties then co-opt"]
        U5S35["I understand the spoiler effect as third-party candidates drawing votes from a major-party candidate in close elections"]
        U5S36["I understand how major parties absorb third-party issues to maintain their dominant position"]
        U5S37["I know what interest groups are — organizations that try to influence public policy without seeking elected office"]
        U5S38["I understand interest group strategies including lobbying, litigation, grassroots mobilization, and electioneering"]
        U5S39["I understand how interest groups use direct lobbying to influence members of Congress and executive agencies"]
        U5S40["I understand how interest groups use litigation and amicus curiae briefs (friend-of-the-court arguments from outside groups) to influence judicial decisions"]
        U5S41["I understand how interest groups mobilize members through grassroots campaigns, protests, and letter-writing"]
        U5S42["I can tell the difference between economic groups, public interest groups, single-issue groups, and ideological groups"]
        U5S43["I understand the free-rider problem (people benefiting from a group's work without helping) as individuals benefiting from group efforts without contributing"]
        U5S44["I understand how PACs raise money from members and contribute to candidates campaigns within legal limits"]
        U5S45["I understand how Super PACs can raise and spend unlimited funds on independent expenditures"]
        U5S46["I understand Citizens United v. FEC ruling that independent political spending by corporations and unions is protected speech"]
        U5S47["I understand how Citizens United v. FEC increased the role of outside money in American elections"]
        U5S48["I understand the revolving door (people going back and forth between government jobs and lobbying) as movement of individuals between government positions and lobbying firms"]
        U5S49["I understand the presidential election process from primaries through the general election"]
        U5S50["I understand how primaries and caucuses allow party members to select their partys presidential nominee"]
        U5S51["I can explain the differences between open primaries allowing any voter to participate with closed primaries limited to registered party members"]
        U5S52["I understand the Electoral College as the constitutional mechanism for electing the president"]
        U5S53["I know that a candidate needs 270 of 538 electoral votes to win the presidency"]
        U5S54["I know that most states use a winner-take-all system for allocating electoral votes"]
        U5S55["I understand how the Electoral College can produce a president who loses the national popular vote"]
        U5S56["I understand how the Electoral College system causes candidates to focus on competitive swing states"]
        U5S57["I understand the role of national party conventions in formally nominating the presidential and vice-presidential candidates"]
        U5S58["I understand how the primary process frontloads early states giving them disproportionate influence"]
        U5S59["I understand the advantages of incumbency in congressional elections including high reelection rates"]
        U5S60["I know incumbency advantages, including name recognition, franking privilege (free mailings to constituents), casework, and fundraising advantages"]
        U5S61["I know what gerrymandering (drawing district lines to give one party an advantage) means — the manipulation of legislative district boundaries for political advantage"]
        U5S62["I understand Shaw v. Reno ruling that racially motivated gerrymandering (drawing district lines to give one party an advantage) must be subject to strict scrutiny (the toughest legal test for government actions)"]
        U5S63["I can tell the difference between partisan gerrymandering (drawing district lines to give one party an advantage) and racial gerrymandering (drawing district lines to give one party an advantage)"]
        U5S64["I understand how gerrymandering (drawing district lines to give one party an advantage) creates safe seats and reduces electoral competition"]
        U5S65["I understand how midterm elections frequently result in the presidents party losing congressional seats"]
        U5S66["I understand how modern campaigns are candidate-centered relying on personal organizations rather than party machines"]
        U5S67["I understand the role of campaign consultants, pollsters, focus groups, and media strategists in modern campaigns"]
        U5S68["I understand how campaigns use microtargeting (using data to send personalized messages to specific voters) and data analytics to identify and mobilize potential supporters"]
        U5S69["I understand how social media platforms have transformed campaign communication and voter engagement"]
        U5S70["I understand the Federal Election Campaign Act as establishing contribution limits and disclosure requirements"]
        U5S71["I understand the role of the Federal Election Commission in administering and enforcing federal campaign finance law"]
        U5S72["I understand the Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act as banning soft money contributions to national party committees"]
        U5S73["I understand how Citizens United v. FEC struck down portions of BCRA restricting corporate independent expenditures"]
        U5S74["I understand the ongoing debate between regulating campaign finance to prevent corruption and protecting political speech"]
        U5S75["I understand the role of the media as a linkage institution (something that connects the government to the people) connecting government to the public"]
        U5S76["I understand how media agenda-setting (deciding which issues get attention) influences which issues the public and government consider important"]
        U5S77["I know what gatekeeping (deciding what gets covered and what doesn't) is — the medias power to choose which stories to cover and which to ignore"]
        U5S78["I know what horse-race journalism (covering who's winning instead of actual policy) is — coverage focused on who is winning rather than substantive policy issues"]
        U5S79["I understand the watchdog role of the media in investigating and reporting on government actions"]
        U5S80["I understand how the decline of traditional media sources has affected investigative journalism"]
        U5S81["I understand how the rise of cable news, internet media, and social media has fragmented the media landscape"]
        U5S82["I understand how media fragmentation has contributed to political polarization and echo chambers"]
        U5S83["I understand the impact of ideological media outlets on reinforcing existing political beliefs"]
        U5S84["I understand how misinformation and disinformation spread through digital and social media platforms"]
        U5S85["I understand the transition from broadcast network news dominance to a diverse and decentralized media environment"]
        U5S86["I understand how changes in media consumption patterns affect political knowledge and civic engagement"]
